'''Jasleen Dhamija''' (born 1933 <ref name=ht/>) is a veteran Indian textile art historian, crafts expert and former UN worker.<ref name=today>{{cite web | title = Jasleen Dhamija looks beyond embroidery at the people responsible for it |work=India Today| url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/jasleen-dhamija-looks-beyond-embroidery-at-the-people-responsible-for-it/1/231554.html |author=Labonita Ghosh|date=29 October 2001|accessdate = 2014-10-09  }}</ref> Based in Delhi, she is best known for her pioneering research on the handloom and handicraft industry, especially history of textiles and costumes.<ref name=hindu>{{cite web | title = Drapes and divinity - The Hindu | url = http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/jasleen-dhamija-editor-of-sacred-textiles-of-india/article6241449.ece |author=Sangeeta Barooah Pisharoty|date=23 July 2014| accessdate = 2014-10-09  }}</ref><ref name=su/> She has remained professor of living cultural traditions at the [[University of Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web | title = The interpretation of yarns |work=India Today | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/The+interpretation+of+yarns/1/25407.html |author=Damayanti Datta|date=16 January 2009 | accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref> Over the years, during her career as a textile revivalist and scholar, she has authored several books on textiles, including ''Sacred Textiles of India'' (2014).<ref name=hindu/><ref>{{cite web | title = Weaving holy traditions |work=MiD DAY| url = http://www.mid-day.com/articles/weaving-holy-traditions/15569199 |author=Dhara Vora |date=1 Sep 2014| accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref>

==Early life and background==
Dhamija grew up in [[Abbotabad]], in the North Western Frontier Province, before her family migrated to Delhi in 1940, where they lived in Khyber Pass locality of [[Civil Lines, Delhi]], and graduated from [[Miranda House]], University of Delhi.<ref name=ht>{{cite web | title = India in the 1940s: The way we were|work= Hindustan Times | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/brunch-stories/india-in-the-1940s-the-way-we-were/article1-1106116.aspx |date=10 August 2013| accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Of people and places: Jasleen Dhamija | url = http://www.india-seminar.com/2002/515/515%20jasleen%20dhamija.htm |work=Indian-seminar|date=2002| accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref>

==Career==
She started her career in 1954,  with culture and craft revivalist [[Kamaladevi Chattopadhyay]] in the Government of India, and started working on craft revival, community development and women's employment.<ref>{{cite web | title = ‘South has preserved crafts successfully so far’ |work= The New Indian Express | url = http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article1324776.ece|author=Janani Sampath|date=3 November 2012| accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref><ref name=craft>{{cite web | title = Dhamija, Jasleen|work=craftrevival.org| url = http://www.craftrevival.org/voiceDetails.asp?Code=258 
| accessdate = 2014-10-09 }}</ref> In the 1960s, she worked with the Handicrafts Board of India, next she started working with artisans directly in rural area, this in time lead to her work with the UN developing self-help programmes for women in war-torn Balkan countries.<ref name=today/>

Over the years, she has curated several textile and crafts exhibitions.<ref name=craft/> Besides several books, on crafts and textile, she has also written two cookbooks, including ''Joy of Vegetarian Cooking'' (2000). In 2007, she published a biography of Kamaladevi Chattopadhyay and her role in the revival of the arts and crafts in modern India.<ref>{{cite web | title =Paperback Pickings|work= The Telegraph - Calcutta| url =http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070316/asp/opinion/story_7520545.asp |date=16 March 2007| accessdate = 2014-10-09  }}</ref>

She has remained faculty at the [[National Institute of Fashion Technology]], New Delhi, where she taught History of Indian Textiles and costumes.<ref name=su>{{cite web |title=Jasleen Dhamija| url = http://www.sutratextilestudies.com/Jasleen%20Dhamija.pdf |work=Sutra Textile Studies| accessdate = 2014-10-09  }}</ref>

